**Code Explanation:**

The code performs the visualization tasks requested in the research plan: 1. LCA Metrics Plot: Since the original LCA metrics were not explicitly saved, we fit a Gaussian Mixture Model (GMM) on the job security indicators (QEA_2 and QEB_2) for 2 to 5 components as a proxy. We calculate and plot the BIC, AIC, and Entropy across the number of classes to help determine the optimal number of latent trajectories. 2. Heatmap of Class-Conditional Probabilities: We calculate the proportion of respondents in each response category (from Significantly Negative to Significantly Positive) for both current and future job security, conditional on their assigned LCA_Class. This is visualized as a heatmap to characterize the psychological state of each class. 3. Predicted Probability Curves: We train a multinomial logistic regression to predict LCA_Class membership using the QKB_Index (Organizational Enablers) and QGO_Index (Company Culture). We then simulate and plot the predicted probabilities across the range of each index while holding the other at its mean. 4. Interaction Plot: We identify the "Resiliently Optimistic" class as the one with the highest mean combined job security score. We then fit a binary logistic regression predicting membership in this class using Regular Training (QKB_1_4), Employee Involvement (QKB_1_11), and their interaction. The plot shows how the probability of being in this optimistic class changes with Employee Involvement at different levels (Minimum, Median, Maximum) of Regular Training. 5. Random Forest Feature Importance: We load the permutation importance results for Job_Security_Future generated in Step 5 and create a horizontal bar chart of the top 20 predictors, including error bars representing the standard deviation across cross-validation folds.

**Modifications:**

The code has been updated to address the overlapping y-axis labels in the Random Forest Permutation Importances plot (Image 4). Instead of wrapping the text (which caused vertical overlap due to the number of bars), the predictor names are now strictly truncated to a maximum of 60 characters, appending an ellipsis ("...") if they exceed this length. This ensures each label occupies only a single line, preventing vertical overlap. Additionally, the figure size has been adjusted to (12, 10), and plt.tight_layout() is used to ensure the left margin accommodates the truncated labels properly.

